---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout title="Investments">

    <nav id="sidebar">
        <a href="/">← Home</a>
        <h1>Investments</h1>
        <ul id="toc"></ul>
    </nav>

    <main>
        <section class="intro">
            <h1>Founders are exceptional people.</h1>
            <p>
                They are prepared to bet years of their life to make something they are passionate about come alive.
                I love learning from Founders. Sometimes, when I meet someone really special, I invest. I invest if I
                think I can add value and make money.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="investment">
            <h2 id="lovable">Lovable</h2>
            <p>
                I invested in Lovable because Anton Osika is the right kind of crazy. He is bold and pushes for a
                more aggressive, ambitious mindset in Europe. Anton and co-founder Fabian have what it takes to
                build something huge. Building "the last piece of software" is a great mission.
                <a href="https://lovable.dev/" target="_blank">Link</a>
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="investment">
            <h2 id="nyctea">Nyctea</h2>
            <p>
                I invested in Nyctea because I've been consistently impressed by founder and CEO Dr.
                Gustav Ferrand-Drake. Nyctea is on a mission to create affordable medicine by reducing the cost of
                production. Through his research, Gustav has invented a new method of biopharmaceutical
                purification.
                <a href="https://nycteatechnologies.com/" target="_blank">Link</a>
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="investment">
            <h2 id="intui">Intui</h2>
            <p>
                I invested in Intui because I was intrigued by its mission to reinvent the way machine learning
                works. It's a bold and crazy ambition. Dr. Henrik Jörntell has spent his career understanding the
                neural basis of sensorimotor control. His conclusion is that modern machine learning is based on a
                long-since outdated understanding of the brain.
                <a href="https://www.intui.ai/" target="_blank">Link</a>
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="investment">
            <h2 id="motorica">Motorica</h2>
            <p>
                I invested in Motorica because I think the best way to build value using machine learning is to
                create a unique dataset. Motorica's vision of "motion without capture" is a great example of this.
                Their dataset of human motion is unique and allows for very low-cost generation of human motion.
                <a href="https://www.motorica.ai/" target="_blank">Link</a>
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="investment">
            <h2 id="normain">Normain</h2>
            <p>
                I invested in Normain because I'm very impressed by Sara and Dennis Landfors. They have the
                experience, determination, and judgement to build a great company. AI is perfect for offloading
                boring work like compliance, auditing, due diligence, and sustainability. Normain aims to take AI
                from perfect in theory to perfect in practice.
                <a href="https://normain.com/" target="_blank">Link</a>
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="investment">
            <h2 id="redpine">Redpine</h2>
            <p>
                I've spent most of my career obsessing about data. Access to high-quality data is one of the best ways to improve performance.
                It turns out that only a small fraction of the world's data is openly available, which leaves AI agents grounded in generic insights. Redpine provides a "grounding API" that connects models to licensed, non-public data — scientific, legal, financial and other proprietary
                sources — while handling compliance, licensing and provenance.
                I'm excited to back founders Anders Hammarbäck and David Österdahl in their effort to solve one of the real bottlenecks to trustworthy AI: hallucinations caused by
                missing data.
                <a href="https://www.redpine.ai/" target="_blank">Link</a>
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="investment">
            <h2 id="incredible">Incredible</h2>
            <p>
                Founder Philip Alm is curious, hard-working and fast-moving, and has been experimenting with
                AI solutions since before most. I decided to back him and the team because they are
                relentlessly exploring ways to improve the usability of AI. I think "vibe computing", i.e.
                controlling your computer using voice, has the potential to be a huge unlock for productivity.
                <a href="https://www.incredible.one/" target="_blank">Link</a>
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="investment">
            <h2 id="minute">Minute</h2>
            <p>
                Ludvig Bartholdsson is a crazy guy. He has been building stuff his whole life, and refuses
                to settle. One of the things I love about him is that he decided to take on telecom as his
                domain. That's unusual, but it's a huge market with slow incumbents. I'm excited to see
                where his journey takes him.
                <a href="https://minute.com/" target="_blank">Link</a>
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="investment">
            <h2 id="120ft-factory">120ft Factory</h2>
            <p>
                I grew up as a robotics nerd. When I came across Martin Willers and his vision to build
                autonomous micro-factories, I couldn't resist backing him. He envisions container-sized
                production lines run by physical AI and robotics, making local, on-demand manufacturing
                possible. It's an ambitious bet, and I'm excited to see how it plays out.
                <a href="https://120ftfactory.com/" target="_blank">Link</a>
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="investment">
            <h2 id="inception-fund">Inception Fund</h2>
            <p>
                Oliver and I go way back. We met when he was at Peltarion, and we had just started Kognic. Since then, I've seen him grow into an extremely well-connected and thoughtful investor.
                I decided to join Inception Fund as a Venture Partner and LP because I wanted exposure to the very best technical AI founders in the Nordics. Inception is a
                fast-moving micro-fund that writes small first checks into inception and pre-seed AI and
                deeptech companies across Sweden, Finland, Estonia and beyond. Backing a great early-stage
                fund is a good way to place many uncorrelated bets alongside someone who sees far more young
                AI teams than I ever could on my own.
                <a href="https://inceptionfund.vc/" target="_blank">Link</a>
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="investment">
            <h2 id="off-piste-fund">Off Piste Fund</h2>
            <p>
                I decided to back Max Samuel and Off Piste Fund I because I'm drawn to his sharp, independent
                analysis. We invested together in Intui, and spent time on their board together. Max has a fascinating background, spending close to a decade working next to Peter Thiel at Thiel
                Capital. He was a GP at SNÖ Ventures before setting out as a solo GP. I always enjoy discussing things with Max!
                <a href="https://offpiste.capital/" target="_blank">Link</a>
            </p>
        </section>
    </main>

    <script>
        document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", () => {
            const toc = document.getElementById("toc");
            const headings = document.querySelectorAll("main.index-main h2[id]");

            headings.forEach((heading) => {
                const li = document.createElement("li");
                const a = document.createElement("a");
                a.href = `#${heading.id}`;
                a.textContent = heading.textContent;
                li.appendChild(a);
                toc.appendChild(li);
            });
        });
    </script>
</BaseLayout>
